NAME
	pcapstreamer - dump packets into stdout

SYNOPSIS
	# pcapstreamer

DESCRIPTION
	This is a very simple tool capable of dumping every packets from linux's 'any'
	interface to stdout in a human readable byte strings. This is a linux specific tool.

	This tool uses libpcap to capture packets. you need to have libpcap headers to
	compile. Here is the way to compile in fedora,

		 # yum install libpcap-devel
		 # yum install glib2-devel
		 # yum install glibc-devel

		 $ git clone github.com/mohan43u/pcapstreamer
		 $ cd pcapstreamer
		 $ make
		 # ./pcapstreamer
	
	You need to be root to listen on 'any' interface.

EXAMPLE
	# ./pcapstreamer
	[cl:77 l:77 t:20111225083853.940215] 00000000 00000100 00000010 00000000
	 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000
	 00000000 00000000 00001000 00000000 01000101 00000000 00000000 00111101
	 10100011 10101110 01000000 00000000 01000000 00010001 01000011 00101010
	 01110011 11110001 10011110 11011011 11011100 11100010 01100100 00101000
	 11001110 11100110 00000000 00110101 00000000 00101001 00010100 00110111
	 00111110 01111101 00000001 00000000 00000000 00000001 00000000 00000000
	 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000100 01110100 01100001 01101100
	 01101011 00000110 01100111 01101111 01101111 01100111 01101100 01100101
	 00000011 01100011 01101111 01101101 00000000 00000000 00000001 00000000
	 00000001

	 Here, 'cl' indicates 'captured length', 'l' indicates 'length' and 't'
	 represents 'captured timestamp'. To decode this packet, you should 
	 refer to http://www.tcpdump.org/linktypes/LINKTYPE_LINUX_SLL.html to
	 understand the first 16 bytes. You may need to refer to,
	 http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/cgi-bin/lxr/source/include/linux/if_arp.h to
	 understand 3rd and 4th bytes.
	 
	 This particular packet was going out of my system (first 2 bytes 0x0004, see the
	 LINKTYPE_LINUX_SLL.html) using ppp0 interface (3rd and 4th bytes 0x0200 or
	 decimal 512, see the description in if_arp.h) which is an IP packet (15th and 16th
	 bytes 0x0800, see the description in http://cavebear.com/archive/cavebear/Ethernet/type.html).

SEE ALSO
	pcap(3), tcpdump(1)